# ============================================================================
# IMPORTANT NOTES
# ============================================================================

# Template Repository Notes
#
# This repository contains template .gitignore files in the following
# subdirectories:
#   - common/        (10 templates for common patterns)
#   - languages/     (28 templates for programming languages)
#   - frameworks/    (30 templates for web frameworks)
#   - tools/         (30 templates for build tools and utilities)
#   - editors/       (8 templates for code editors and IDEs)
#   - operating-systems/ (3 templates for operating systems)
#   - platforms/     (2 templates for development platforms)
#
# These template files are NOT for this repository itself. They are examples
# for users to include in their own projects. The patterns in this file
# (root .gitignore) are specifically for this repository's development.
#
# This repository should NOT contain:
#   - Actual project dependencies (node_modules/, vendor/, etc.)
#   - Framework-specific build directories (.next/, .nuxt/, etc.)
#   - Application build outputs (build/, dist/, out/) from template examples
#   - Real environment files with sensitive data (.env with actual secrets)
#
# If you find any of the above in this repository, they are likely development
# artifacts that should be cleaned up, not template examples.

# ============================================================================
# USER GUIDANCE
# ============================================================================
# For users looking to create .gitignore files for their own projects:

# 1. Use specific template files from subdirectories:
#    ```bash
#    cp languages/python.gitignore .gitignore
#    ```

# 2. Combine multiple templates:
#    ```bash
#    cat languages/python.gitignore common/security.gitignore > .gitignore
#    ```

# 3. Use common patterns from the common/ directory:
#    ```bash
#    cat common/security.gitignore common/dependencies.gitignore > .gitignore
#    ```

# 4. See README.md for comprehensive usage instructions and examples.

# ============================================================================
# STANDARD TEMPLATE STRUCTURE
# ============================================================================
# All templates in this repository follow this standard structure:
#
# 1. Header with source attribution
# 2. Brief description of the technology
# 3. Technology-specific patterns (organized by category)
# 4. References to common patterns
# 5. Usage notes and combination examples
# 6. Links to official sources (if applicable)
